      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walk Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":378,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 3-minute brisk walk to warm up the foot and get blood flowing before any running. This is non-negotiable — cold starts are one of the biggest triggers for plantar fasciitis flare-ups.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run easy at the slower end of your easy pace range (5:45–5:58 /km). At the first hint of any foot discomfort, drop to a walk immediately — no pushing through. Think conversational effort: you should be able to speak in full sentences without gasping.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":378,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk gently for 3 minutes. Finish with calf stretches and plantar fascia stretching — gently pull your toes back toward your shin while seated. This helps maintain tissue mobility after loading.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3-minute brisk walk before any running. Do not skip this — cold tissues are vulnerable tissues, especially with active plantar fasciitis.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3-minute walk, followed by seated plantar fascia stretch (toe extension) and standing calf stretch against a wall. Hold each for 30–45 seconds. These are part of the workout, not optional extras.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Welcome back, James. This first run of the week is all about reintroducing load gently and gathering information — how does the foot respond? Your physio has cleared you for 20 minutes of easy running, so we stay exactly within that boundary. The pace target here is the slower end of your easy range (around 5:45–5:58 /km), which for your VDOT 46.5 is genuinely physiologically productive for aerobic base rebuilding — easy running at this effort stimulates mitochondrial development and capillary density even without any speed work. The most important data point from this run is foot feedback: note when any discomfort starts (if at all), how it feels afterward, and how it feels the next morning. Morning-after heel pain is a key plantar fasciitis signal. Walk breaks are not a concession — they are a smart load management tool your physio has specifically prescribed.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run — Foot Check-In\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":378,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk warmup. Roll your foot gently on a tennis ball before heading out — 60 seconds each foot — to mobilize the plantar fascia before loading it.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy conversational pace, slower end of easy range. Use a 4-minute run / 1-minute walk pattern if the foot feels anything above a 2/10 discomfort during Tuesday's run. If Tuesday felt completely clear, you can run the 14 minutes continuously — but stay at easy pace and stay honest with yourself.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":378,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk cooldown. Repeat calf and plantar fascia stretching. Consider icing the heel for 10–15 minutes post-run if there was any soreness — this can help manage inflammation without disrupting training.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Pre-run foot roll (tennis ball or frozen water bottle, 60 seconds) then 3-minute walk. This helps desensitize the plantar fascia tissue before impact loading.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3-minute walk, then plantar fascia stretch and calf stretch as on Tuesday. Ice heel if any soreness was present during the run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This midweek run builds on Tuesday's session. The key question here is: how did the foot respond in the 24–48 hours after Tuesday? If morning-after heel pain was absent or minimal (1–2/10), you can approach this run with more confidence. If the foot was grumpy, use the run-walk structure (4 min run / 1 min walk) to reduce cumulative load. This run serves the same physiological purpose as Tuesday — aerobic stimulus at easy effort — but it also gives us a second data point on foot tolerance, which is invaluable for planning next week. Keeping two days between runs (Tuesday and Thursday) gives connective tissue adequate recovery time. Plantar fascia is largely avascular — it heals slowly, and load management across the week matters as much as load within a session.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Long Run — Easy Effort, 20-Minute Cap\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":368,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":368,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":378,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk. Take an extra minute here if the foot feels stiff — stiffness first thing in the morning is common with plantar fasciitis and typically eases with gentle movement.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":368,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy effort at a comfortable pace within your easy range (5:24–5:58 /km). Aim for the middle of the range today — around 5:45 /km. This is your 'long run' for now, which simply means it's the run that gets the most intention and care this week. No pace pressure. If the foot speaks up, walk.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":378,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes. Do your full stretching routine — plantar fascia, calves, hip flexors. Saturday is also a good day for extra self-care: foam roll your calves (tight calves increase plantar fascia strain), and consider an ice bath for the foot if you have one available.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3-minute walk. If foot stiffness is present (very common in the morning with plantar fasciitis), extend the walk warmup by 2–3 minutes before transitioning to running. Do not rush the warmup on your longest effort day.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Full stretching routine: plantar fascia stretch, standing calf stretch (both straight and bent knee to target both gastrocnemius and soleus), hip flexors. Foam roll calves if available. Ice the foot for 15 minutes if any soreness was felt.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your Saturday run is designated as your 'long run' per your preference — and while 20 minutes feels modest compared to where you were pre-injury, this is exactly the right call for where you are right now. Here's the physiological rationale: your aerobic base doesn't vanish during injury layoff as fast as it feels like it does. With 5 years of training history, you retain significant neuromuscular and cardiovascular adaptation. What does degrade faster is connective tissue tolerance — tendons, fascia, and ligaments lose load-bearing capacity during reduced activity. So the gap right now isn't your lungs or your heart — it's your foot's capacity to absorb impact. That's precisely why we're capping at 20 minutes and keeping pace easy. The goal for this week is three runs completed, foot happy, no flare-up. That's a genuinely successful week. What would be a win for you personally from this first week back?\",\"perceived_effort\":4}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
